context: <a0_0><b5_0>Old English<b5_0/><a0_0/> (Ænglisc, Anglisc, Englisc) or <b6_0>Anglo-Saxon<b6_0/> is the earliest historical form of the English language, spoken in England and <a1_0>southern and eastern<a1_0/> Scotland in <a2_0>the early Middle Ages<a2_0/>. It was brought to Great Britain by <a3_0><b7_0>Anglo-Saxon settlers<b7_0/><a3_0/> probably in the mid 5th century, and <b8_0>the first Old English literary works<b8_0/> date from the mid 7th century. After the Norman Conquest of 1066, English was replaced for a time as the language of the upper classes by Anglo-Norman, a relative of French, and Old English developed into the next historical form of English, known as <a4_0>Middle English<a4_0/>.
